testCodes.description: Occult (Hidden) Blood can be low levels of Red Blood cells or hemoglobin whose low concentration does not color the urine but whose presence is still unexpected.
testCodes.label: Occult blood

testCodes.description: WBC (White Blood Cells) aren’t expected in the urine, but a few may be seen in a normal urine sample. Their presence indicates inflammation and potential infection.
testCodes.label: WBC

testCodes.description: RBCs (Red Blood Cells) aren’t expected in the urine, but a few may be seen in a normal urine sample. Their presence means something’s off – usually inflammation somewhere in the urinary tract.
testCodes.label: RBC

testCodes.description: Cast always originate from the kidneys. They form in the tubules of the kidney and can be comprised of many things – from RBCs to a waxy substance. Casts are unexpected findings and usually require further testing to find out more.
testCodes.label: Casts/LPF

testCodes.description: Struvite (Triple Phosphate) crystals are the most common crystals dogs experience. They can increase the risk for urolith (stone) formation. Their significance must be examined in light of urine pH, Specific Gravity, and diet.
testCodes.label: Struvite (Triple PO4) crystals

testCodes.description: Bacteria is an unexpected finding in a urine sample, since urine is sterile. If collection was done through a “free catch,” some bacteria can be expected. If the sample was collected via sterile methods, bacteria usually indicates potential infection. Further testing may be needed.
testCodes.label: Bacteria

testCodes.description: Epithelial cells come from the lining along the urinary tract, starting at the kidneys. Their significance depends on the amount, how the urine sample was collected, and which other components are present. A few of these cells can be expected.
testCodes.label: Epithelial cells

testCodes.description: While protein is not commonly found in urine, small amounts may appear.  Larger amounts of protein will require follow-up.
testCodes.label: Protein

testCodes.description: While glucose is not commonly found in urine, small amounts may appear due to stress.  Larger amounts of glucose will require follow-up.
testCodes.label: Glucose-Strip

testCodes.description: While ketones are not commonly found in urine, small amounts may appear.  Larger amounts of ketones will require follow-up.
testCodes.label: Ketones

testCodes.description: While bilirubin is not commonly found in urine, small amounts may appear.  Larger amounts of bilirubin will require follow-up.
testCodes.label: Bilirubin
